    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Threat to Irish Peace</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel J Donovan letter comments on Oct 20 editorial on threat to Northern Ireland peace process from members of hard-line Ulster Unionist Party</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 20 editorial conveys the new threat to the peace process from hard-line Ulster Unionist Party officials. Rather than stepping up to the challenges of peace, some party members are calling on their community to retreat into the hopelessness of mistrust and to view reforms, which are beneficial to all, as a defeat for their movement.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>An Oct. 20 editorial conveys the new threat to the peace process from hard-line Ulster Unionist Party officials. Rather than stepping up to the challenges of peace, some party members are calling on their community to retreat into the hopelessness of mistrust and to view reforms, which are beneficial to all, as a defeat for their movement.</p>
        <p>We have seen recently how the people of Serbia replaced a discredited leadership with one that offers policies intended to make Serbia a normal, democratic European nation. The people of the Unionist community should follow this example. They should insist on leaders who value political and social reforms, instead of those who try to revive ancient animosities.</p>
        <p>DANIEL J. DONOVAN  Brooklyn, Oct. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
